human.', 'document_classification': 'HUMAN_ONLY', 'version': '2025-01-09-base', 'language': 'en', 'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Menu A lawmaker is facing criticism for showing off his firearm at Indiana\'s Statehouse this week. State Rep. Jim Lucas says he was demonstrating that firearms are everywhere when he showed his holstered handgun to a group of teens on Tuesday. A 10-minute video of the Seymour Republican\'s debate with Muncie high school students was posted on social media Wednesday. Lucas told Scripps News Indianapolis he was trying to show "that guns are among us, and living in fear of them does not make sense." Lucas says he met the students in an elevator Tuesday and stepped off to speak with them. The students are from the Burris Laboratory School in Muncie and are members of Students Demand Action. They were in Indianapolis to urge lawmakers to do more to prevent gun violence as part of a day of action, a spokesperson for event organizers said. About six minutes into the video, a student tells Lucas that Australia banned guns and hasn\'t had a mass shooting in years. "They\'re not free," Lucas says in the video. "You’re not truly free if you can’t defend yourself." "So, do you mean by carrying?" a student asks. "I’m carrying a gun right now," Lucas says, opening his suit jacket and showing a holstered weapon on his hip. In the video a student\'s voice says, "See, and nothing about that makes me feel safe." Lucas told Scripps News Indianapolis he was trying to have an "adult conversation" with the students and didn’t know he was being recorded. When asked if he would do anything differently regarding his meeting with the students, Lucas said, "Maybe not falsely assume that they were ready to have an adult conversation." The incident drew criticism on social media, with some accusing him of brandishing, and others calling for him to leave his role. "Indiana GOP Rep. Jim Lucas, who flashed his gun at kids, needs to step down," said X user Annie Tomlin. Another X user, Karen Johnson wrote, "So embarrassed that he \'represents Indiana. We can do better than this." On Facebook, Lucas spoke out after the video made its rounds online. "I had a very interesting discussion today at the Statehouse with a small group of young ladies and their teacher that were with the group Students Demand Action," Lucas wrote. "The conversation was respectful, but it was clearly facts, reason and logic vs. plain emotion. I also learned afterwards that you must always assume that you’re being recorded, because you probably are," he continued. In a separate post, he went on to say, "I fear for, and pity those that are being indoctrinated to fear that which is their best means of self defense." This story was originally published by Vic Ryckaert at Scripps News Indianapolis. Trending stories at Scrippsnews.com'}]

'pageNumber': 0, 'inputText': 'Partly cloudy with an isolated chance of a passing afternoon thunderstorm. Winds N 5-10 mph.. Updated: June 1, 2024 @ 4:00 pm FOX23 breaks down the earthquake from Friday evening which is tied for fourth strongest felt in Oklahoma. People could feel shaking across Green Country Friday night into Saturday morning after earthquakes near Prague, including a 5.1 magnitude quake. The United States Geological Survey (USGS) reported a 5.1 magnitude quake near the Lincoln County town of Prague. (Image from USGS Interactive Map) The quake was reported at 11:24 p.m. Friday night about 4.9 miles northwest of Prague. The USGS also reported a 2.6 magnitude quake at 11:36 p.m. and a 3.5 magnitude quake at 12:32 a.m., both about 4.9 miles northwest of Prague. The USGS classifies earthquakes with a 5 to 5.9 magnitude as moderate earthquakes. The quake was felt in both the Oklahoma City and Tulsa metro areas. Prague is about 60 miles southwest of Tulsa. At 10:20 a.m. on Saturday, Lincoln County Emergency Management said no injuries have been reported so far. On Saturday afternoon, the Oklahoma Corporation Commission announced all disposal wells that are permitted to dispose into the Arbuckle formation and are in within 10 miles of the 5.1 magnitude quake were directed to begin shutting down, with a shutdown to be completed by Feb. 17. The Commission said the gradual shutdown process is necessary to avoid sudden pressure changes that could result in more seismic activity. The Commission also said oil and gas wastewater disposal into the Arbuckle formation has been linked to seismic activity and that further study may result in new directives. FOX23\'s Shae Rozzi asked viewers about the earthquake on social media. One woman in Bixby said she thought it was thunder at first. "Bixby. I thought it was thunder, it rumbled really loud. Then the house started shaking including walls and moved my bed. It was really scary," said Beverly Parker. Friday\'s earthquake is smaller than the one many Oklahomans remember in 2016. That earthquake occurred on Sept. 3, 2016 in Pawnee, Oklahoma and was 5.8 magnitude. The Pawnee earthquake was the strongest recorded earthquake in state history. preventing symptomatic infection in adults, according to the first U.S. study to assess how well the shots work. The shots became available last year and were designed to better protect against more recent coronavirus variants. In Thursday's study, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention looked at 9,000 people who got tested for COVID-19 at CVS and Walgreens pharmacies, checking who tested positive and whether they had gotten a new shot or not. The 54% finding is similar to what's been reported in other countries, and it's also about what was reported for an earlier vaccine version, said the Ruth Link-Gelles of the CDC, the study's lead author. Studies coming out later this year will assess how effective the shot was at preventing symptoms severe enough to send patients to a doctor's office or hospital, she said. The CDC recommends the new shots for everyone 6 months and older, but most Americans haven't gotten them. The latest CDC data suggests only about 22% of U.S. adults have gotten the shots, and only 11% of children. (Image from National Transportation Safety Board) HYDRO, Okla. — Several geese carcasses were found in the debris field of a deadly Air Evac helicopter accident, including one embedded in part of the helicopter, according to a preliminary report from the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB). The accident happened on Jan. 20, killing pilot Russell Haslam, flight nurse Adam Tebben and medic Steven FitzGerald, according to Air Evac Lifeteam. According to the NSTB report, the accident happened at 11:23 p.m. The helicopter had dropped off a patient at an Oklahoma City hospital and was returning to their home base in Weatherford, about 70 miles west of Oklahoma City. The report said the company GPS monitoring program stopped tracking the helicopter at around 11:30 p.m. and a search began for the helicopter. The wreckage was found in an open pasture about 1.5 miles east of Hydro, which is about 8 miles east of Weatherford. According to the report, several geese carcasses were found in the debris field, including one embedded in a flight control servo. The report said a review of the US Air Force’s Avian Hazard Advisory System found the probability of bird activity as “low” in the area of the accident. Samples of geese feathers were recovered for more detailed identification, according to the report. The report said all major parts of the helicopter were found at the accident site. The transmission had separated from the fuselage and was found at the site. Both the white main rotor blade and red main rotor blades were fractured. The mast nut had separated and was located in the debris field. The helicopter was retained for further examination, according to the report. Air Evac Lifeteam said Global Medical Response will be holding a memorial service on Feb. 6 to celebrate the life of the crew. It will take place at 1 p.m. at the Pioneer Cellular Event Center in Weatherford. Three crew members onboard an Air Evac Lifeteam helicopter died after a helicopter crash, according to a statement released by Air Evac Lifeteam.
